column168: VII & VIII ABOVE: NO PACKAGING FAILURE INVOLVED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  THIS SPILL WAS CAUSED BY HUMAN ERROR.  OUR DRIVER WAS PUMPING A LOAD OF DIESEL FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TNAK.  OUR DRIVER FAILED TO SECURE THE CAP ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE PRODUCT PUMP AND IT VIBRATED OFF SPILLING 30+ GALLONS OF DIESEL ONTO THE GROUND.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY SUPERVISED THE CLEANUP. ALL OF THE CONTAMINATED DIRT WAS REMOVED THE SAME DAY. ON MONDAY, JULY 25, 1994 AT 12:00 PM, DELTA DISTRIBUTORS, INC. ST. GABRIEL, LA., DELIVERED A LOAD OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID TO A CUSTOMER - BAKER PERFORMANCE CHEMICAL IN LAUREL, MS.  WHEN AIR WAS PUT ON THE TRAILER TO UNLOAD THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID, THE FLANGE ON TOP THE TRAILER LEAKED AND ABOUT 55 GALLONS OF ACID LEAKED UNTO THE GROUND.  THE ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND LIMESTONE.  THE DOME LID WAS JUST REPLACED ON THE TRAILER AND BAKER PERFORMANCE WAS THE FIRST LOAD OF ACID TO BE PUMPED OFF OF THE TRAILER.  THE BOLTS ON THE FLANGE OF THE DOME LID WERE NOT TIGHTENED DOWN ENOUGH WHICH CAUSED THE FLANGE NOT TO SEAL PROPERLY ON THE TRAILER.  WHEN AIR PRESSURE WAS ADDED TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT, THE ACID CAME OUT OF THE LOOSE DOME TOP FLANGE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0700 HOURS ON JULY 3, 1994, PERSONNEL WORKING THE WEST JACKSONVILLE YARD OBSERVED INTERMODAL TANK CONTAINER SUTU 103364, EMITTING A VAPOR FROM THE OUTLET VALVE OF THE CONTAINER. SUTU 103364 WAS PLACED ON FLAT CAR TTAX 653152. TO FACILITATE INSPECTION OF THE SUBJECT CONTAINER, THE CONTAINER AND FLAT CAR WERE MOVED TO THE CSX INTERMODAL RAMP ADJACENT TO THE WEST JACKSONVILLE YARD. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE INTERMODAL RAMP, PERSONNEL OBSERVED A LIQUID DRIPPING UPON THE SURFACE OF THE FLAT CAR. DUE TO THE FLAMMABE NATURE OF THE LADING, THE JACKSONVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED TO RESPOND TO THE INTERMODAL RAMP. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT THE IMMEDIATE AREA SURROUNDING THE SUBJECT WERE EVACUATED UNTIL THE LEAK WAS SECURED. THERE WERE NO EVACUATIONS OF CIVILIANS OR PERSONS OFF CSX PROPERTY. INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER WAS MADE BY CSX PERSONNEL. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FLANGE CONNECTING THE OUTLET VALVE TO THE CONTAINER BODY WAS LEAKING AT A MINOR RATE. MEMBERS OF THE JACKSONVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM TIGHTENED THE BOLTS SECURING THE FLANGE. AT THIS POINT THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. CONTAINMENT WAS PLACED AROUND THE VALVE AND FLANGE IN THE EVENT THE FLANGE LEAKED AGAIN. APPROXIMATELY ONE (1) GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE BODY OF THE FLAT CAR. THIS WAS NEUTRALIZED AND RECOVERED WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT. THE CONTAINER WAS TRANSFERRED TO A HIGHWAY VEHICLE ON JULY 5, 1994, AND CARRIED ON TO ITS DESTINATION.

AFTER APPLYING PRESSURE PRODUCT ESCAPED FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER.  HE SHUT DOWN AND IN CHECKING THE TRAILER FOUND THAT HE HAD FAILED TO CLOSE ONE OF THE TWO AIR VALVES ON TOP OF THE TRAILER.  THE CUSTOMER FLUSHED THE AREA WITH WATER AND AFTER CLOSING THE VALVE OUR DRIVER COMPLETED THE DELIVERY WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.

HOW DID THE RELEASE OCCUR?  THE RELEASE ORIGINATED FROM A LEAKING DRUM IN A ROSS TRANSPORATION SERVICE'S TRAILER.  A DRUM LEAKED AND SUBSEQUENTLY LEAKED THROUGH THE TRAILER FLOOR ONTO THE GROUND.  THE RELEASE WAS TO THE GROUND.  A DRUM WAS USED TO COLLECT THE LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE TRAILER. THE LIQUID ON THE GROUND WAS EXCAVATED WITH A BACKHOE AND PLACED INTO DRUMS.  A TOTAL OF 22 DRUMS OF SPILL CLEANUP WAS REMEDIATED.  THE SPILL CLEANUP WILL BE INCINERATED AT ROSS INCINERATION SERVICES, INC.

WHILE ENROUTE FROM OUR NEW JOHNSONVILLE, TN FACILITY TO VENEZUELA, AN ODOR OF HYDROGEN SULFIDE WAS DETECTED IN THE CONTAINER AT THE PORT OF HOUSTON. A MATHESON BRANCH MANAGER SURVEYED THE CONTAINER ON 07/21/94 AND 07/22/94. A SMALL LEAK WAS FOUND ON ONE OF THE FUSIBLE PLUGS ON TANK CAR TANK SERIAL #SG 895428.  THE LEAK STOPPED WITH A SEALING DEVICE AND THE UNIT WAS REMOVED TO THE MATHESON FACILITY IN LAPORTE, TX, WHERE IT WAS TRANSFILLED. IT IS BELIEVED THE INTENSE HEAT IN THE CONTAINER RESULTING FROM AMBIENT TEMPERATURES NEAR 100 O F RESULTED IN PREMATURE MELTING AND EXTRUSION OF THE 163F FUSE PLUG EUTECTIC MATERIAL AT A TEMPERATURE BELOW 163 O F.  A SMALL LEAK PATH RESULTED, ALLOWING ABOUT 0.05 GRAMS OF H2S TO ESCAPE IN 24HOURS.  THIS IS BELIEVED TO BE A RANDOM OCCURENCE WHICH WAS EXACERBATED BY THE UNUSUALLY HOT WEATHER.

SUBJECT DRUM WAS PICKED UP ON 6/28/94 ON INDIANA HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST INA 0938009 (SEE ATTACHED COPY) THE LOAD OF DRUMS WAS BROUGHT TO THE ST. LOUIS WAREHOUSE WHERE IT WAS UNLOADED FORM THE ORIGINAL TRAILER FOR CONSOLIDATION AND TRANSSHIPMENT TO SUPERIOR'S INDIANAPOLIS WAREHOUSE, FOR SUBSEQUENT SHIPMENT TO THE RECEIVING FACILITY. THE SUBJECT CONTAINER WAS PLACED IN WAREHOUSE STORAGE. OPERATIONS WERE SHUT DOWN OVER THE HOLIDAY WEEKEND (JULY 2-4). WHILE IN STORAGE, THE TEMPERATURE IN THE WAREHOUSE, ROSE TO AN ESTIMATED 120 DEG. F. THE CONTAINED WASTE, A MIXTURE OF POLY AND VINYL ESTERS, CALCIUM CARBONATE, AND A PEROXY BENZOATE CATALYST BEGAN TO REACT. THE REACTION THAT TOOK PLACE WAS EXOTHERMIC, CAUSING CONTINUED CATALYZATION OF THE CONTAINED WASTE. THE ENSUING PRESSURE RISE IN THE CONTAINER CAUSED IT TO EXPAND, AND FINALLY BURST THE HEAD OFF THE DRUM. THIS BURSTING ACTION CAUSED NEARLY HALF OF ITS CONTENTS TO BE RELEASED. THE MATERIAL RELEASED WAS IN THE FORM OF A TACKY TO DRY SOLID POLYMERIZED RESIN. AT 0730 ON 7/5, THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED. OTHER DRUMS WERE REACTING IN A SIMILAR MANNER AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIONS WERE INITIATED. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS BROUGHT ON SITE TO COOL THE CONTAINERS. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF WITH THE BALANCE OF THE WASTE SHIPMENT, IN A MANNER CONSISTENT WITH STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATION. THE PACKAGING MATERIALS PERFORMED ADMIRABLE, GIVEN THE CIRCUMSTANCES, WITH ONLY ONE CONTAINER FAILING. UNPOLYMERIZED RESIN SYSTEMS WILL NO LONGER BE STORED IN AREAS WITH UNCONTROLLED ATMOSPHERES.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR LOGEX DRIVER WAS ROUNDING A VERY TIGHT CURVE ON KENTUCKY RT 192 AT ABOUT 3-5 MPH. HE HAD TO MOVE OVER THE CENTERLINE OF THE HWY. WITH HIS TRACTOR TO KEEP THE RIGHT REAR TRAILER TANDEMS ON THE PAVED PORTION OF THE HIGHWAY. AS HE WAS NEGOTIATING THE CURVE, TRAFFIC WAS COMING TOWARD HIM FROM THE OPPOSITE DIRECTION, OUR DRIVER MOVED BACK TO HIS LANE, IN DOING SO THE REAR TANDEMS SLID INTO CONCRETE CULVERT. THE TRAILER ROCKED TO THE RIGHT SIDE AND SLOWLY ROLLED OVER ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE. NO INJURIES OCCURRED. THE TRAILER REMAINED STABLE, NO PRESSURE RISE OR PRODUCT LOSS. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT VENTING THE PRODUCT WOULD BE NECESSARY TO UPRIGHT THE VEHICLE, THE TRAILER WAS SLOWLY VENTED OVER A 9 HOUR PERIOD. THE HUMIDITY WAS HIGH & THIS CONDITION ALLOWED THE LIQUID NITROGEN TO DISSAPATE INTO THE ATMOSPHERE, VERY LITTLE LIQUID TOUCHED THE GROUND.

column168: DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING DOWN HILL ON RT 56 APPROACHING RT. 422.  HE STATED THAT THE BRAKES WENT SOFT AND SOULD NOT STOP UNIT TO MAKE TURN.  HE PROCEEDED STRAIGHT AND KEPT TRYING TO STOP UNIT.  THERE IS A 90 DEGREE LEFT BEND AT THE BOTTOM OF THE HILL.  THE TRUCK WENT AROUND THE TURN AND LAID OVER ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE, CONTACTING A SMALL GUARD RAIL AND THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT BEFORE COMING TO REST AT THE EDGE OF TE CITY PARK. EMERGENCY RESPONDED TEAMS WERE CALLED TO MITIGATE THE SPILL. THE TRUCK WAS RIGHTED AND REMOVED, AND A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND RESTORE THE AREA TO ORIGINAL CONDITION.

column168: THE SEQUENCE OF EVENTS THAT LED TO THE INCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION.  THE NATIONAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY BOARD WILL PREPARE A REPORT IN APPROXIMATELY 5 TO 6 MONTHS.  THE ACTION TAKEN WHEN NOTIFIED OF THE ACCIDENT AT APPROXIMATELY 2 AM WAS IMMEDIATE RESPONSE TO THE SCENE. WE AREA IN THE PROCESS OF REVIEWING THE ACCIDENT TO DETERMINE A COURSE OF ACTION TO PREVENT A REOCCURANCE OF A SIMILAR ACCIDENT.

DRIVER REPORTED THAT HE WAS AWAKENED BY FIRE DEPARTMENT AT SAAP BROS. T/S IN CHEYENNE WY. BECAUSE THERE WAS SOME LIQUID LEAKING FROM REAR OF TRAILER.  THE AREA AROUND TRAILER WAS SECURED BY FIRE OFFICIALS AND CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED BY SAFETY DEPARTMENT OF THE SPILL.  THE MSDS WERE FAXED TO FIRE CHEIF AND SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  RYDELL ENVIRONEMTAL RESPONSE TEAM WAS AUTHROIZED TO RESPOND ARRIVED ABOUT 3 HRS AFTER INITIAL REPORT AND CLEANED UP SPILL OUTSIDE AND INSIDE TRAILER AND PLACED EXPOSED MATERIAL AND DRUM WITH REMAINING PRODUCT IN AN OVERPACK FOR SHIPMENT TO DESTINATION, WHERE IT WAS SENT BACK TO SHIPPER VIA AND LTL CARRIER FOR DISPOSAL AND RECOVERY.  VARIOUS WITNESS AT SCENE INDICATED THE LEAK APPEARED TO THE RESULT OF FORKLIFT DAMAGE THAT WEAKENED THE DRUM AND WITH HIGH ELEVATION CAUSED PRODUCT TO EXPAND AND LEAK.

DRIVER WAS PUMPING PRODUCT FROM UNDERGROUND TANK, HE WAS ON TOP OF THE TRAILER MONITORING FLOOR FLOW OF PRODUCT INTO COMPARTMENT #1 (3100 CAPACITY).  DRIVER STATED HE WAS GOING TO FILL TO 3000 GALLONS.  WHEN PRODUCT WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 1/2 FROM THE 3000 GALLON MARKER, THE DRIVER STARTED TOWARDS BACK OF TRAILER AND CLIMBED DOWN LADDER.  DRIVER WALKED AROUND TO SIDE OF TRAILER AND TURNED VALVE OFF.  HE THOUGHT BY SHUTTING VALVE OFF THAT THIS WOULD STOP FLOW OF PRODUCT AND GIVE HIM TIME TO TURN TRACTOR PUMP OFF.  AS DRIVER WAS GETTING INTO TRACTOR HE HEARD SOMEONE YELLING THAT PRODUCT WAS FLOWING OFF BACK OF TRAILER.  DRIVER THEN TURNED THE RPM SWITCH OFF (LEFT PUMP AT IDLE SPEED), WENT TO INVESTIGATE THE SITUATION AT REAR OF TRAILER.  AT THIS POINT, THE DRIVER THOUGHT THAT THE PRODUCT COMING OFF REAR OF TRAILER HAD STOPPED BECAUSE HE HAD SHUT VALVE OFF AND TURNED PUMP TO IDLE.  DRIVER THEN WENT TO PASSENGER SIDE OF TRAILER AND UNCOUPLED ONE EAR ON HOSE TO CHANGE COMPARTMENTS.  PUMP WAS STILL AT IDLE SPEED AND PUMPING PRODUCT, THE PRESSURE FROM THE PRODUCT BEING PUMPED AGAINST CLOSED VALVES PUSHED HOSE BACK AND SPILLED PRODUCT ON GROUND.  DRIVER YELLED FOR HELP (HE STILL WAS HOLDING HOSE IN HAND), THE PROJECT MANGER ON SITE JUMPED INTO TRUCK AND SHUT PUMP OFF.  DRIVER THEN COUPLED HOSE BACK TO COMPARTMENT #1.  THE CONSTRUCTION SUPERINTENDENT ASKED DRIVER IF HE WANTED SOME TOPSOIL PUT ON THE FUEL IN ORDER TO CONTAIN IT; DRIVER SAID YES.  TOPSOIL WAS THEN PUT ON FUEL AND SPREAD OUT OVER THE SPILL SITE.  DRIVER THEN COMPLETED PUMPOUT AND CALLED TERM MGR. INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICES HANDLED CLEANUP.
DISCOVERED CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  DISCOVERED THE LIQUID VALVE TO BE LOOSE.  TIGHTENED VALVE AND RELEASED CAR TO DESTINATION.  NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT.

ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS BROUGHT IN AND CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF AT LOCAL LANDFILL WITH PRIOR ILLINOIS EPA APPROVAL. AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER MADE A CALL TO THE EMERGENCY BREAKDOWN TEAM IN RICHMOND VA. THE CALL WAS THEN MADE TO THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM IN ST. PETER, MO. ALSO THE OFFICALS AT OVERNITE IN ST. LOUIS WERE CONTACTED, AND THEY CALLED RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES. THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED BY THE FIRE DEPT., AND CONTAINED BY RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC.

I REALIZE THAT THIS PACKAGE HAS AN EXCEPTION AND I ALSO REALIZE THAT THE CAUSE WAS IMPROPER HANDLING FROM OUR LIFT OPERATOR CAUSING THE PUNCTURE. MY CONCERN IS THAT SINCE THIS IS REGULATED AND CONSIDERED HAZ. MAT. THERE IS NO PROTECTION ON THE CONTAINER, SPECIALLY AROUND THE LOWER AREA WHERE THE FORKLIFTS ARE REQUIRED TO MOVE THEM. THIS IS ALSO A POTENTIAL DANGER FROM OTHER FREIGHT WHICH COULD SLIDE INTO IT IN AN ACCIDENT. I ALSO REALIZE THAT PROPER HANDLING, BLOCKING, BRACING IS THE KEY TO SAFE TRANSPORTATION OF ANY FREIGHT BOTH HAZARDOUS AND NON-HAZARDOUS. I HAVE ENCLOSED A PHOTO OF THE CONTAINER FOR YOUR RECORDS. THANK YOU. THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS WHEN THE LIFT OPERATOR WAS UNLOADING THE TOTE FROM ONE TRAILER TO ANOTHER FOR ITS DESTINATION AND ACCIDENTALLY HAD THE FORKS SLIGHTLY HIGHER THAN EXPECTED CAUSING THE BLADE TO ENTER BETWEEN THE PALLET AND THE CARDBOARD CONTAINER.

OUR DRIVER WAS DRUMMING OFF THE PRODUCT INTO A TOTE WHEN HE SHUT OFF THE INTERNAL VALVE AND THE HOSE END POPPED PUT OF THE TOTE SPILLING A RESIDUE OF THE MATERIAL THAT WAS IN THE HOSE. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY OUR DRIVER AND DISPOSED OF BY THE CONSIGNEE.

PRODUCT LEAKED FORM DAMAGED DRUM ONTO CARDBOARD PLACED UNDER THE DRUM DURING TRANSIT AND HAD EVAPORATED AND WAS DRY BY THE TIME THE SHIPMENT WAS UNLOADED. HOLE IN DRUM WAS TAPED SHUT: CUSTOMER ACCEPTED RECEIPT OF DAMAGED DRUM AND DISPOSED OF IT AT THEIR FACILITY. DUNNAGE TO BE USED IN FUTURE WITH MORE CARE TAKEN AS TO WEIGHT LOADED ON TOP.
PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ACTIVATED RELEASING PRODUCT BECAUSE TRAILER WAS ON AN INCLINE. ACCURATE AIR GAUGE AND LEVEL TANK WILL PREVENT REOCCURANCE.
FITTING VIBRATED OFF WHILE UNLOADING, RESULTING IN A SPILL OF 40 TO 50 GALLONS. DRIVER COUNSELED TO SECURE FITTINGS. MATERIAL CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO DRUMS HAD LOOSE BUNGS. THE TWO DRUMS WERE ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY. THE BUNGS WERE TIGHTENED AND DRUMS PROPERLY RECOOPERED. THE DRUM WERE OVERPACKED INTO NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUMS AND PROPER LABELS APPLIED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. THE SALVAGE DRUMS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRALER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO CARTONS WERE CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT. THE CARTONS WERE IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY. AN INSPECTION FOUND 3 METAL CANS DAMAGED AND LEAKING. THE CARTONS WERE PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH PROPER LABELS AND MARKINGS. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO DRUMS WERE LEAKING AT THEIR ROLLING HOOPS. THE DRUMS WERE ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY. THE DRUMS WERE PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH PROPER LABELS AND MARKINGS. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. THE SALVAGE DRUM WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT.

CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. ("CHESI") WAS DISPATCHED TO MARTIN MARIETTA, INCORPORATED ("MMI") LOCATED AT 10 LAKESIDE AVENUE IN BURLINGTON, VT TO PICK-UP A LOAD OF WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S. (CHROMIC AND SOLUTION). UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SITE, THE CHESI DRIVER WAS DIRECTED MMI EMPLOYEE TO THE FIRST STORAGE TANK THAT WAS TO BE PUMPED OUT. THE MMI EMPLOYEE CONNECTED THE TRANSFER HOSE TO THE TANKS TO BE PUMPED OUT WHILE THE CHESI DRIVER ATTACHED THE HOSE TO THE VEHICLE. UPON COMPLETION OF THIS TASK, THE TRANSFER OPERATION WAS INITIATED (PLEASE NOTE THAT THE PRODUCT IN QUESTION WAS BEING PUMPED INTO THE REAR COMPARTMENT OF A SPLIT COMPARTMENT CARGO DISCOVERED THAT PALE YELLOW VAPORS WERE COMING FROM THE VENT STACK OF THE SCRUBBER SYSTEM ON THE CARGO TANK. THE TRANSFER WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND THE VAPORS SUBSIDED. MMI THEN HOOKED UP TO A SECOND TANK THAT CONTAINED IDENTICAL MATERIAL AND RESUMED THE PUMPING OPERATION BUT WAS FORCED TO STOP THE TRANSFER AS VAPORS AGAIN BEGAN ESCAPING FROM THE VENT STACK. AT THIS POINT, THE CHESI DRIVER REFUSED TO ACCEPT ADDITIONAL MATERIAL FROM THIS TANK. THE DRIVER WAS THEN DIRECTED TO PUMP A THIRD TANK INTO THE FRONT COMPARTMENT AND PRIOR TO CONDUCTING THIS TRANSFER, MMI EMPLOYEES FLUSHED THE TRANSFER HOSES WITH WATER AND ADDED THIS RINSE WATER TO THE REAR COMPARTMENT. THE TRANSFER OF THE THIRD TANK WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE DRIVER THEN PREPARED THE VEHICLE AND ALL ANCILLARY EQUIPMENT FOR TRANSPORTATION AND PROCEEDED TO THE GUARD SHACK AT MMI TO OBTAIN ALL REQUIRED PAPERWORK AND SIGNATURES. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE, THE DRIVER CONDUCTED ONE LAST CHECK OF THE LOAD AND DISCOVERED THAT THE REAR COMPARTMENT OF THE CARGO TANK WAS HOT TO THE TOUCH. HE IMMEDIATELY INFORMED MMI THAT THE LOAD WAS NOT SAFE TO TRANSFER AND RETURNED THE VEHICLE TO THE CONTAINMENT PAD IN THE EVENT OF A CONTAINER FAILURE. THE CHESI DRIVER THEN CONTACTED HIS HOME OFFICE TO APPRAISE THEM OF THE SITUATION WHO IN-TURN CONTACTED MMI TO IDENTIFY POTENTIAL CAUSES OF THE REACTION. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE MATERIAL PUMPED INTO THE CARGO TANK WAS NOT A CHROMIC ACID SOLUTION AS INDICATED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE STORAGE TANKS BUT RATHER A MIXTURE OF NITRIC, SULFURIC, HYDROCHLORIC AND PHOSPHORIC ACIDS. THIS MIXTURE IS INCOMPATIBLE WITH A STAINLESS STEEL TANK AND BECAUSE OF THIS, CHESI REQUESTED THAT STEPS BE TAKEN TO OFF-LOAD THE VEHICLE TO PREVENT BOTH A MAJOR RELEASE AND FURTHER DAMAGE TO THE CARGO TANK. THE REACTION INSIDE THE TANK CONTINUED AND VAPORS WERE BEING GIVEN OFF THROUGH THE VENT SYSTEM OF THE CARGO TANK. IN RESPONSE TO THE INCIDENT, MMI HIRED AN OUTSIDE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT AS CHESI WAS NEVER IN CONTROL OF THE LOAD NOR THE LOADING PROCEDURES. WHILE PREPARING A RESPONSE PLAN, A WATER SPRAY WAS USED BY MMI'S CONTRACTOR TO CONTROL THE INCREASED TEMPERATURE OF THE TANK CAUSED BY THE REACTION BETWEEN THE LADING, THE LINING OF THE TANK AND THE WATER THAT MMI ADDED TO THE LOAD. THE DECISION

column168: (A B & C) A SECOND VEHICLE WAS OVER THE CENTER LINE CAUSING OUR DRIVER TO VEER TO  HIS RIGHT, OFF THE PAVED SURFACE. (THE AREA IS COMPRISED OF A SERIES OF SMALL HILLS.) HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO BEGIN A SIDEWAYS SLIDE. AS HE STARTED BACK UPON THE PAVEMENT, THE VEHICLE FLIPPED OVER,ROLLING TWICE AND COMING TO REST UPRIGHT ON PARTMENTALIZED TANKS STRIPPED THE THREADS OFF THREE (3) OF THE FOUR (4) RODS WHICH HOLD THE TANKS ON THE TRUCK BED. THE TANKS MOVED, CAUSING THE PIPING TO TEAR LOOSE AND BREAK, LETTING THE CHEMICAL SPILL FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. LARGER RADIUS RODS WITH DOUBLE NUTS WILL BE UTILIZED ON ALL FUTURE MANUFACTURED UNITS AND REPAIRS TO PRESENT UNITS WILL BE ACCOMPLISHED AS QUICKLY AS THEY CAN BE RELEASED FOR UPDATING. NOTIFICATIONS OF D.O.T. TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCES CONSERVATION COMMISSION, TEXAS HIGHWAY PATROL, WOOD COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE MADE AS SOON AS WE COULD POSSIBLY DO IT. THE DISTRICT MANAGER FROM KILGORE, TEXAS WAS ON THE SCENE WITHIN 30 MINUTES AND DIRECTED THE CLEAN-UP

DRIVER HAS TO HOOK UP A VENT LINE AND DISCHARGE (UNLOADING) LINE. AFTER HOOKING UP HOSE TO VENT LINE, DRIVER STARTED TO HOOK UP DISCHARGE HOSE. AS HE MOVED HOSE, ABOUT 4 OR 5 DROPS LEAKED OUT AND VAPOR SMOKE WAS COMING OUT OF HOSE. FOREMAN SHUT DOWN AREA. DRIVER AND UNLOADER MOVED INTO TANK BUILDING AWAY FROM VAPOR. DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT UNLOADER OPENED VALVES TO STORAGE TANK AND PRESSURE FROM VENT LINE PUSHED INTO LIQUID LINE THROUGH A STRUCK CHECK VALVE IN NITROGEN BLOW-DOWN SYSTEM. AFTER VALVE WAS SHUT AREA CLEARED AND FOREMAN CHECKED AREA AND ALLOWED PERSONNEL BACK. PRODUCT WAS STEAM CLEANED AND CARGO TANK WAS UNLOADED WITHOUT ANYMORE PROBLEMS.

WHILE PERFORMING TRACK WORK, MAINTENANCE OF WAY PERSONNEL NOTIFIED THE DISPATCHER THAT A TANK CAR IN TRAIN 125-25 APPEARED TO BE LEAKING LADING FROM FITTINGS AT THE TOP OF THE CAR.  BURLINTON NOTHERN RESPONSE TEAM MEMBERS MET THE TRAIN ON LINE.  INSPECTION OF TANK CAR ECUX 405482, NAPHTHA, COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID, UN1256, PG111, REVEALED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM A PARTIALLY OPEN VAVE AND LOOSE PLUG ON THE LIQUID LINE. INCREASING INTERNAL PRESSURE RESULTING FROM HIGHER TEMPERATURES WAS FORCING LADING THROUGH THE LIQUID LINE.  THE VALVE HANDLES HAD BEEN LEFT IN PARTIALLY OPEN POSITIONS IN ORDER TO CLOSE THE COVER THE VALVES.  AFTER THE VALVES WERE CLOSED AND THE PLUGS TIGHTENED WRENCH TIGHT, THE VALVE HANDLES WERE REMOVED AND WIRED THE VALVES TO ALLOW THE COVER TO BE PROPERLY CLOSED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

WHILE TRAIN 193-21 WAS PASSING THROUGH BOULDER COUNTY, COLARDO, A VAPOR CLOUD WAS OBSERVED OVER THREE TANK CARS AND A STRONG ODOR INDICATED THAT THERE WAS LEAKAGE FROM ONE OF THE TANK CARS.  THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED BY THE BOULDER COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT.  INSPECTION OF THE TANK CARS BY THE BOULDER COUNTY HAZ MAT TEAM REVEALED THAT TANK CAR GATX 3908, AMMONIUM SULFIDE SOLUTION, 8, UN2683, PG 11, HAD A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET. TEMPORARY REPAIRS WERE MADE BEFORE THE CAR WAS SET OUT AT A LOCATION WHERE IT COULD BE HELD UNTIL PERMANENT REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.  THE SHIPPER MADE THE NECESSARY PERMANENT REPAIRS AND RELEASED THE CAR ON JULY 13, 1994 FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

column168: THE COLUMBIA & COWLITZ TRAIN CREW WAS TRANSPORTING GATX 12954 FROM THE SOLVAY INTEROX PLANT SITE AT 3500 INDUSTRIAL WAY, LONGVIEW, WA. TO THE NORPAC PAPER CO. PLANT SITE.  JUST INSIDE THE MILL-SITE, THE TRAIN CREW STOPPED, THEN COUPLED TO A BOX CAR.  AFTER COUPLING TO THE AR THEY FIRST NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM THE TOP PART OF THE RAILCAR.  THEY IMMEDIATELY STOPPED AND CALLED FOR RESPONSE FROM THE SOLVAY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND FROM THE COMPANY OWNED FIRE DEPARTMENT.  BOTH RESPONDED PROMPTLY.  THE CONDUCTOR PROVIDED AN MSDS TO THE RESPONDING FIREMAN AND STOOD BY WHILE THE SOLVAY INTEROX TEAM INVESTIGATED THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL AND UPON IDENTIFICATION OF THE CAUSE, REPLACED THE RAILCARS RUPTURE DISC.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE SOLVAY TEAM COOPERATED TO ENSURE THE SPILL WAS DILUTED WITH WATER.  THE TRAIN CREW WAS THEN AUTHORIZED TO CONTINUE MOVEMENT OF GATX 12954 TO ITS DESTINATION.  THE RUPTURE DISC WAS FOUND FUNCTIONAL UPON DEPARTURE FROM THE SOLVAY INTEROX PLANT SITE.  NO LEAKAGE OCCURED IN TRANSIT UNTIL THE INCIDENT AT NORPACK.  LEAKAGE MAY HAVE BEGAN FOLLOWING THE COUPLING OF THE TRAIN TO THE BOX CAR.  THE INVESTIGATIO OF THE INCIDENT FOLLIWNG THE COUPLING OF THE TRAIN TO THE BOX CAR.  THE INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT INDICATED THAT THE APPROPRIATE FRANGIBLE DISC (RUPTURE DISC) WAS IN USE ON THE RAILCAR AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. COLUMBIA & COWLITZ RAILWAY WILL CONTINUE TOREVIEW ITS HANDLING.

column168: OUR TRUCK AND TRAILER #33-33A WAS INVOLVED IN A VEHICLE ACCIDENT CAUSING BOTH UNITS TO GO OFF THE FREEWAY AND TRAILER OVERTURNING.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM REPUBLIC WARNER ENGINEERED STEELS LOCATED AT 2633 8TH ST NORTHEAST IN CANTON, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL ST IN BALTIMORE, MD. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S CLEVELAND SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 2940 INDEPENDENCE RD IN CLEVELAND, OH IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 TO 8 OUNCES OF LEAD AND CADMIUM CONTAMINATED BAG HOUSE DUST AHD ACCUMUATED AROUND THE BOTTO OF ONE OF THE BULK BAGS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT RESIDUAL MATERIAL WAS ON THE OUSDIE OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS WHEN IT WAS PICKED UP AND DURING THE COURSE OF TRANSPORTATION THE RESIDUAL MATERIAL FELL OFF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY RECONTAINERIZED THE MATERIAL AND REMOVED ALL RESIDUE FROM THE OUTSIDE OF THE CONTAINER.  ALL CLEAN UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO THE BULK BAG AND WAS THEN DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN REINSTRUCTED TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND IF RESIDUAL MATERIAL IS FOUND ON THE EXTERIOR OF A CONTAINER THAT THE RESIDUAL MUST BE REMOVED OR THE MATERIAL RECONTANERIZED PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.

DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT BLADE WHILE PALLET WAS BEING MOVED IN FRONT OF DRUM.  DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE OF RECOVERY DRUM.  SHIPPER AUTHORIZED RETURN OF PRODUCT FOR REPACKAGING.  ALL DOCK WORKERS ADVISED TO NOT FULLY EXTEND FORK BLADES ON SHIPMENTS LOADED IN FRONT OF DRUMS.

ON JULY 19,1994, I WAS DISPATCHED WITH A LOAD OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID GOING TO STEWART & STEVENSONS IN THE CITY OF CAMARILLO IN CALIFORNIA.  UPON ARRIVAL TO THE PLANT, I PROCEEDED GOING TO THE CONTROL ROOM AND TELLING THE OPERATOR WHAT I WAS DELIVERING, HIS NAME WAS DALE HELIN.  AFTER BACKING THE TRUCK INTO POSITION, I BOLTED MY DISCHARGE HOSE OPENING TO THE TANK INLET VALVE.  AFTER CHECKING FOR LEAKS, WHICH THERE WERE NONE, AND SEEING THAT THE FLOW OF LIQUID WAS FLOWING INTO THE TANK WITHOUT ANY PROBLEMS, THE OPERATOR TOLD ME HE HAD TO GO BACK TO THE CONTROL ROOM TO KEEP AN EYE ON THE CONTROL PANEL WHICH I TOLD HIM WAS OK.  AFTER APPROXIMATELY 5 T 7 MINUTES LATER, I WAS LEANING AGANST THE REAR FENDER OF THE TRAILER WITH MY BACK TO THE DISCHARGE VALVE WHEN I HEARD A LOUD NOISE IMMEDIATELY I TURNED AROUND AND SAW THAT THE DISCHARGE HOSE HAD COME APART FROM THE FLANGE.  I IMMEDIATELY RAN UP THE STAIRS OF THE TRAILER AND TURNED THE DISCHARGE VALVE OFF, ALSO TURNED THE AIR SUPPLY OFF AND WENT INTO THE OPERATORS ROOM, TO INFORM HIM OF WHAT JUST OCCURRED.  HE CALLED A COUPLE OF HIS COWORKERS AND WHEN WE GOT BACK TO THE AREA WE PUT ON OUR SAFETY GEAR AND RESPIRATORS, WE THEN PROCEEDED ON NEUTRALIZING THE ACID, (HCL) WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE WHICH IS AN ACID NEUTRALIZER.  AT THIS TIME, THE PLANT MANAGER WAS INFORMED, JEFF WHITE.  AFTER GOING OVER THE SITUATION WE NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  WHEN THEY ARRIVED, THEY SURVEYED THE SITUATION AND AFTER DETERMINING THE SPILL HAD BEEN CONTAINED TO A SMALL AREA, AND MOST OF THE ACID HAD BEEN NEUTALIZED, FIREOFFICER RON KEUSER STATED THEY COULDN'T DO ANYTHING ELSE, AND THE SITUATION WAS UNDER CONTROL.  THEY LEFT.  AT THAT TIME JEFF WHITE CONTACTED MSE ENVIRONJMENTAL A CLEAN UP COMPANY.  THE SENT OVER A REPRESENTATIVE AND AFTER 30 TO 40 MINUTES TIM DEVIDES ARRIVED.  AFTER SURVEYING THE AREA, HE STATED THEY WOULD HAVE TO PICK UP THE GRAVEL AND DIG UP THE DIRT THAT HAD BEEN CONTAIMINATED.  HE ESTIMATED THAT IT WOULD BE 5 TO 6 DRUMS OF MATERIAL. AFTER SPEAKING WITH JEFF WHITE, THE PLANT MANAGER, HE INFORMED ME THAT HE HAD SPOKEN WITH REYNALDO GARCIA FROM THE INSURANCE COMPANY AT (215) 245-3589 AND THAT MR GARCIA HAD AUTHORIZED THE CLEAN UP.  ALSO A COMPAINES REPRESENTATIVE WAS COMING OVER FROM SANTA BARBARA TO SURVEY THE DAMAGES. AFTER SPEAKING WITH JEFF WHITE AND TIM DAVIDS WE DECIDED THAT TERE WAS NO REASON FOR ME STAY AT THE SITE ANY LONGER.  I ALSO WAS ABLE TO CHANGE THE DAMAGE HOSE AND FINISHED THE DELIVERY;  SOON, THEREAFTER I DEPARTED.
WITH APROXIMATELY 12" OF ROOM LEFT IN THE TANK, DRIVER TRUNED HIS BACK ON TANK TO SPEAK WITH SHIPPERS PERSONNEL REGARDING PREVIOUS DELIVERIES AND TANK OVERFILLED SPILLING OUT THE TOP.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM HAMILTON PRECISION METALS, INC. LOCATED AT 1780 ROHERSTOWN ROAD IN LANCASTER, PA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, IN. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL, CT. DURING THE TRIP, THE DRIVER STOPPED AT A WEIGH STATION LOCATED ON ROUTE 83 SOUTH IN FREELAND,MD WHERE HE WAS INSPECTED BY THE MARYLAND STATE POLICE AND MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT. DURING THIS INSPECTION , THE INSPECTORS NOTED THAT 2 OF THE 55 GALLON CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING FROM THE BUNG CAPS LOCATED ON THE TOP OF THE CONTAINERS AND THAT SEVERAL OF THE DRUMS HAD DISTENDED HEADS CAUSED BY THE HIGH AMBIENT AIR TEMPERATURE. PLEASE NOT THE CONTAINERS AND WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DECISION WAS MADE TO LOOSEN THE BUNGS ON THE DRUMS TO RELIEVE THE PRESSURE AND TO DISPATCH A CLEAN HARBOR'S FIELD SERVICE CREW TO PLACE THE CONTAINERS INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUMS. UPON ARRIVAL, THE FIELD SERVICE CREW PLACED THE CONTAINERS IN QUESTION INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUMS. UPON COMPLETION OF THIS OPERATION, THE CONTAINERS WERE SENT TO THE WAST MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST THAT ACCOMPAINED THE SHIPMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE BUNG CAPS ON SEVERAL OF THE DRUMS WERE LEAKING. THE DRIVER REQUESTED THAT THE BUNGS BE REPLACED PRIOR TO THEM BEING LOADED ONTO THE VEHICLE. THE BUNG CAPS WERE REPLACED AND EACH CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE IN SHIPPABLE CONDITION. AT THE DRIVER'S NEXT STOP, HE INSPECTED THE CONTAINERS AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WAS THE HIGH AMBIENT AIR TEMPERATURE COUPLED WITH NOT PROVIDING ENOUGH HEAD SPACE IN THE CONTAINERS TO ALLOW FOR MATERIAL EXPANSION. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, THE SHIPPER WILL BE NOTIFIED AS TO THE SUSPECTED CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT AND WILL BE REQUESTED TO LEAVEE SUFFICIENT HEAD SPACE ON FUTURE SHIPMENTS. IN ADDITION, ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE IN UNSHIPPABLE CONDITION.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, A FORKLIFT PUNCTURED A CARTON.  THE CARTON WAS ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY.  THE CARTON WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH PROPER LABELS AND MARKINGS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO DESINATION.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, A DOCKMAN FOUND TWO CARTONS BY OTHER FREIGHT. THE CARTON WERE ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY.  AN INSPECTION DISCOVERED 12 METAL CANS DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  THE CARTON WERE RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUMS WITH PROPER LABELS AND MARKINGS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

column168: WHEN DOCKMAN WAS LOADING TOTE TANK, HE NOTICED A SMALL DRIP.  HE NOTIFIED CREW LEADER, WHO SAW IT WAS LEAKING FROM THE OUTLET VALVE.  THE VALVE COULD NOT BE TURNED OFF ENOUGH TO STOP THE DRIP, SO HE LOADED IT ON AN EMPTY TRAILER AND COVERED THE FLOOR WITH ABSORBANT MATERIALS.  THE SHIPPER SENT IN A NEW TANK AND A CREW TO TRANSFER THE LEAKING TOTE TO THE NEW TANK.  ALL THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A DRUM AND SENT WITH THE LEAKING TOTE BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

ESTES MAKING A PICK-UP WHEN 20' LONG PIECE OF STEEL PIPE PIERCE DRUM OF SODIUM HYDTOXIDE.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THE LEAKING DRUM AT HIS NEXT STOP AND REPORTED IT TO HIS TERMINAL MANAGER.  GLOBAL SPILL MANAGEMENT WAS ON SCENE.  MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CELANED UP AND STORED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THREE DRUMS WERE RECOVERED AND MANIFESTED TO ENVIRONMENTAL WASTE RESOURCES IN WATERBURY, CT FOR DISPOSAL (MANIFEST ATTACHED) A MEETING WAS HELD WITH LOCAL PERSONNEL TO UNDERSCORE THE NEED TO ENSURE ALL SHIPMENTS ARE PROPERLY SECURED TO PREVENT MOVEMTNT THIS WOULD INCLUDE BOTH HAZMAT AND NON HAZMAT.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: TANK CAR FOUND TO BE VENTING BY CARMAN INSPECTING INBOUND INTERCHANGE CUT FROM U.P.  ATSF RESPONDER DETERMINED SOURCE OF RELEASE TO BE PRODUCT ESCAPING AT SAFETY RELEASE VALVE.  OBSERVATIONS INDICATED A CONTINOUS RELEASE RATHER THAN INTERMITTENT BURSTS, SO THE VALVE DID NOT APPEAR TO BE SEATING. HAMMER MARKS WERE FOUND ON THE VALVE, PERHAPS INDICATING OF PREVIOUS PROBLEMS.  BASED ON THESE FACTS, CAR WAS TRANSLOADED TO PRECLUDE A RECURRANCE.  TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED INTO GOCX 84009.  WRNX 30012 WAS BAD ORDERED FOR DISPOSITION TO REPAIR FACILITY.

UNIT WAS FOUND TO HAVE A LEAK WHEN DRAYMAN WAS MAKING OUT GATE INSPECTION. ATSF RESPONDER ASSESSED LOAD AND FOUND SOURCE OF THE RELEASE TO BE A DRUM AT THE LEFT REAR OF THE LOAD.  THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP HAD AN INWARD DENT AND CRACK.  THIS PRESUMABLY WAS THE RESULT OF IMPROPER LOADING OR WAS DAMAGED PRIOR TO LOADING.  ALTHOUGH THE BLOCK AND BRACING HAD PERMITTED LONGITODINAL VOIDS IN THE LOAD.  THIS IS NOT BELIEVED TO BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR.  THE CONSIGNEE'S RESPONSE TEAM OVERPACKED THE LEAKINNG DRUM.  THE LOAD WAS REBLOCKED FOR THE HIGHWAY MOVE.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: DRIVER IN ROUTE TO SPARKS, NV STOPPED AT TRUCK STOP IN SEIBERT, CO. NOTICED ODOR COMING FROM TRAILER.  DRIVER INVESTIGATED FOUND THAT LOAD LOCK HAD COME LOOSE.  THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM APPEARS TO HAVE OCCURED FROM MOVEMENT WITHIN THE TRAILER.  THE BOTTOM LIP ON 1 DRUM RUBBED THROUGH THE SIDE ON ANOTHER.  RIDEL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO OVERPACK THE DRUM. RELOADED OVERPACK-DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE.  AT 1500 HOURS, TWO RIEDEL PERSONNEL ENTERED THE TRAILER WITH AIR MONITORING EQUIPMENT AND FLASHLIGHTS TO LOCATE THE AFFECTED DRUM(S).  MR. WILSON REMAINED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AS SAFETY WATCH.  THE REMAINING ON-SCENE PERSONNEL STAYED AT THEIR VEHICLES APPROXIMATELY 50 YARDS TO THE SOUTH OF THE TRAILER.  CONTINUOUS AIR MONITORING INDICATED ADEQUATE OXYGEN LEVELS WITHIN THE TRAILER AND NO EXPLOSIVE POTENTIALS.  THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH NINETY-SIX 55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS OF SHERWIN-WILLIAMS LACQUER THINNER. THE SPILL WAS LOCATED AT THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AND INVOLVED ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF LACQUER THINNER.  THE RIEDEL CREW EXITED THE TRAILER AND BEGAN PREPARATION FOR OFFLOADING DRUMS TO REACH THE LEAKING DRUM.  THE RIEDEL STAKEBED TRUCK, WITH THE LIFTGATE DEPLOYED, WAS BACKED UP TO MEET THE FLOOR LEVEL OF THE SCHNEIDER TRAILER.  TWO DRUM HAND CARTS WERE USED BY THE RIEDEL CREW TO BEGIN REMOVAL OF THE LACQUER THINNER DRUMS.  A SERIES OF THREE DRUMS, IN TURN, WERE REMOVED FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO CREATE A PATHWAY TO THE AFFECTED DRUM.  THESE DRUMS WERE PLACED ON THE LIFTGATE, LOWERED TO THE GROUND, AND STAGED APPROXIMATELY TEN FEET TO THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE STAKEBED TRUCK.  A TOTAL OF NINETEEN DRUMS WERE OFFLOADED BEFORE REMEDIATION WORK COMMENCED.    THE LEAKING DRUM WAS RELOCATED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AFTER IT WAS INSPECTED IN PLACED.  A SMALL DENT JUST ABOVE THE BOTTOM SEAM IN THE DRUM WAS OBSERVED WITH THE LACQUER THINNER EXITING AS A SLOW DRIP.  TECHNICIAN COOK TOOK PICTURES OF THE DRUM.  THE RIEDEL CREW THEN USED THE BOOM CRANE ON THE STAKEBED TO LOAD THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO AN 85 GALLON STEEL OVERPACK FOR TRANSPORT.  ALL FREE LIQUID LACQUER THINNER ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS REMEDIATED USING ABSORBANT PADS AND PLACED INSIDE THE OVERPACK BEFORE BEING RESEALED.  A FLAMMABLE LIQUID STICKER WAS PLACED ON THE OVERPACK FOR IDENTIFICATION. TECHINCIAN COOK TOOK A PICTURE OF THE OVERPACK AND REQUESTED FOR CLOSURE OF THE SITE RESPONSE, BUSINESS CARDS EXCHANGED, AND TECHNICIAN COOK AND MR. GUY LEFT SITE TO RESUME OFFICIAL DUTIES.  RIEDEL PERSONNEL RELOADED THE LACQUER THINNER DRUMS FROM THE GROUND USING A BARREL GRABBER AND THE BOOM CRANE.  THESE WERE THEN REPLACED INTO THE TRAILER INTO A TIGHT FITTING ARRANGEMENT THAT WAS SATISFACTORY TO THE SCHNEIDER TRUCK DRIVER. THE OVERPACK WAS SITUATED WITH THE DRUMS AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD.  THE DRIVER THEN PLACED A FOUR FOOT BY EIGHT FOOT SHEET OF PLYWOOD AGAINST THE SIDES OF THE DRUMS AND SECURED THIS WITH A LOAD LOCK.  THE TRAILER DOORS WERE CLOSED AND THE RIEDEL CREW PACKED UP THE STAKEBED TRUCK FOR DE

column168: ON JULY 17, 1994, A TIRE FAILED ON OUR TRAILER TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THE TIRE SUBSEQUENTLY CAUGHT FIRE AND SPREAD TO THE BODY OF THE TRAILER, CAUSING CONSIDERABLE DAMAGE TO THE TRAILER.  AT NO TIME DID ANY OF THE PRODUCT ESCAPE OR LEAK.  AFTER THE INCIDENT, THE TRAILER WAS TRANSPORTED BY FLATBED TO THE GENERATOR (SHIPPER) FOR UNLOADING.  THE COST INCURRED AND REPORTED IN ITEM 23D IS FOR EXPENSES INCURRED BY THE WEST VIRGINIA HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT FOR TRAFFIC CONTROL AND DEBRIS REMOVAL, RATHER THAN ANY DECONTAMINATION.  THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED BECAUSE OF THE BLOCKAGE OF I-64 AND NOT BECAUSE OF THE RELEASE OF ANY HAZARDOUS WASTE.

column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING PROCESSED AND LOADED ON THE OUTBOUND RELOAD WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED BY STATION PERSONNEL. THE PACKAGING HAD BEEN COMPROMISED BY THE LEAKING LIQUID AND HAD A PUNGENT GASOLINE ODOR. THE STATION DG SPECIALIST, MATT DONKIN ISOLATED AND OPENED THE PACKAGE. MR. DUNKIN DISCOVERED THAT SOME TYPE OF ENGINED PUMP WAS IN THE PACKAGE THAT HAD NOT BEEN COMPLETELY PURGED OF GASOLINE. HE ALSO DISCOVERED THAT THIS WAS A PART OF A MULTIPLE PIECE LOT WITH PART OF THE SHIPMENT HAVING ALREADY BEEN LOADED ON A TRUCK BOUND FOR KNOXVILLE, TN. MR. DONKIN NOTIFIED OUR CORPORATE SAFETY ON CALL CONTACT, MARVIN SUDDUTH WHO IMMEDIATELY ORDERED THAT THE PIECES IN TRANSIT HE HELD AND INSPECTED UPON THEIR ARRIVEL IN KNOXVILLE. THE SECONDARY PIECES ARRIVED IN KNOXVILLE AND INSPECTED AND FOUND TO CONTAIN UNDRAINED FUEL. THE ENTIRE 7 PIECE SHIPMENT DID "NOT" EXHIBIT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS. THE F.A.A. IN BOTH NASHVILLE AND TAMPA FLORIDA HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED AND THE PACKAGES ARE BEING HELD FOR INVESTIGATION.

column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED ON THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT INTO THE NORFOLK STATION WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND OPENED TO REVEAL 3 METAL CANS. THESE CANS HOLD APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF MATERIAL EACH. ONE OF THE INNER CONTAINER'S LID APPARENTLY LOOSENED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE SUBSTANCE OUT OF ITS INNER CONTAINER. THE SPILL SPREAD AND WAS NOTICED COMING OUT OF THE OUTER CONTAINER. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE. AN MSDS WAS FAXED TO THE NORFOLK STATION UPON REQUEST. THE FLASHPOINT INDICATED ON THE MSDS WAS LOW ENOUGH FOR THE MATERIAL TO BE CONSIDERED A FLAMMABLE AND REGULATED ITEM. THERE WERE "NO" HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS, LABELS, OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DG THAT WERE ASSOCIATED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE PACKAGE IS BEING HELD AWAITING DISPOSITION AND INVESTIGATION BY THE F.A.A.

CTS, TOM ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED BY SPECIAL AGENT JIM HERRING AND RESPONDED TO ALEXANDRIA INSPECTION BY ROBINSON REVEALED DEFECTIVE GASKETS BENEATH THE LIQUID VALVE AND THE EDUCATION PIPE FLANGE. column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY JEFF HILL, CORRIDOR MANAGER, HARRIMAN DISPATCH CENTER, OMAHA, THAT GARY HUNTER, MANAGER, YARD OPERATION, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, REPORTED A TANK CAR LEAKING IT'S CONTENTS FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED MANAGER HUNTER, WHO STATED ONE OF THE CARMEN REPORTED SMELLING AN UNUSUAL ODOR WHILE WORKING AROUND YARD TRACK #206.  UPON INVESTIGATING THE ODOR, MANAGER HUNTER LOCATED TANK CAR UTLX 201924 IN YARD TRACK #206 LEAKING FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS LEFT IN THE TRACK AND THE AREA SECURED PENDING AN INSPECTION.  THIS CAR ARRIVED YERMO IN THE OGYRB-10 AT 1430 HOURS, TUESDAY, MARCH 12, 1994.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM AROUND THE CLOSURE, AND, AS THE PRODUCT CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE CAR.  AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 85 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT.  THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER HAD A KEEPER/CLOSURE PIN SEAL, UPH 345991, WHICH WAS REMOVED TO ACCESS THE VALVES.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID LINE, PAST THE BALL VALVE, WHICH WAS CLOSED, AND PAST THE AND PAST THE 3 1/2 INCH LINE PLUG, WHICH WAS TIGHT.  THE INTERNAL PRESSURE OF THE CAR WAS DROPPED UTILIZING THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK AT THE LIQUID LINE.  THE LIQUID LINE PLUG WAS REMOVED TO VERIFY THE BALL VALVE WAS CLOSED.  TEFLON TAPE WAS PLACED ON THE THREADS OF THE PLUG PRIOR TO REPLACING AND RE-TIGHTENING.  THE CAR WAS THEN LEFT IN PLACE TO ALLOW THE INTERNAL PRESSURE TO REBUILD.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING THE CAR WAS RE-INSPECTED AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS FOUND LEAKING PAST THE THREADS OF THE LIQUID LINE PLUG.  THE INTERNAL PRESSURE OF CAR WAS AGAIN DROPPED AND AGAIN THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE PLUG WAS REMOVED AND THE THREADS RE-TAPED.  ADDITIONAL FORCE WAS USED TO RE-SECURE THE PLUG.  THE CAR WAS ALSO INSPECTED PRIOR TO DELIVERY TO THE ATSF INTERCHANGE, AND SHOWED NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER DEVELOPED THIS PRODUCT IS LOADED INTO THE CAR UTILIZING A VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM, WHICH, ALLOWS LITTLE OR NO PRESSURE BUILD UP IN THE CAR.  WITH THE DAYTIME AMBIENT TEMPERATURES AT YERMO REACHING APPROXIMATELY 115 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT, PRODUCT EXPANSION WOULD BUILD SUFFICIENT PRESSURE TO FORCE THE LIQUID THROUGH A DEFECTIVE VALVE.  THE SHIPPER WAS TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE CAR SENT TO A REPAIR FACILITY AND HAVE THE VALVE REPLACED, ONCE IT WAS MADE EMPTY BY THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC; STATE OF CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, REPORT #003092; COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES; AND THE SHIPPER, COASTAL CHEM.  NO FURTHER ACTION IS REQUIRED ON THIS INCIDENT AS ALL OF THE RELEASED PRODUCT HAS EVAPORATED.

column168: ON 6-28-94 A PACKAGE CONTAINING A COMPOUND A CORROSIVE LIQUID N.O.S. (ALKALINE AMINE) WAS SHIPPED CLEARLY LABELED AS A HAZARDOUS CORROSIVE FROM TAMMS CORP. LOCATED ON EMPIRE ST IN WILES-BARRE. IN TRANSIT, THE PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED, AN INSPECTION WAS DONE ON THE DAMAGED PACKAGEBY R. SCHOENSTER AND D. BUFFA THE FIRST BEING A CLERK AND THE SECOND BEING A SUPERVISOR FROM THE RONKONKOMA CTR (1173) IN THE LONG ISLAND DIST. AFTER THE INSPECTION WAS COMPLETED THE PKG WAS INCORRECTLY REPACKED AND NOT LABELED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. UPON BEING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER, IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING THROUGH THE SIDE OF THE BOX IT WAS RETURNED IN. AFTER INSPECTING THE PACKAGE MR. RAY MAREK THE PLANT MGR OF TAMMS CALLED UPS TO LET US KNOW ABOUT THIS SITUATION AND WANTED TO KNOW IF SOMEONE COULD COME OUT TO DISCUSS THE PROBLEM. ON WED. JULY 6 1994 I VISITED TAMMS CORP. TO DISCUSS THE PROBLEM OF THE LEAKING PACKAGE WITH MR RAY MAREK. HE EXPLAINED TO ME WHAT TYPE OF CHEMICAL WAS IN THE CARTON AND HOW DANGEROUS IT COULD BE IF IT CAME IN CONTACT WITH SKIN OR WAS INGESTED EVEN IN VERY SMALL QUANTITIES. AFTER DISCUSSING THE PACKAGE WITH RAY MAREK I ASSURED HIM THAT THE PROBLEM WOULD BE CORRECTED AND APOLOGISED FOR ANY INCONVENIENCE HE HAD ENCOUNTERED. I PLAN TO FOLLOW-UP WITH MR. MAREK ON 7-7-94 TO LET HIM KNOW OUR PLAN OF ACTION TO KEEP PROBLEM FOR REOCCURRING IN THE FUTURE. THIS WAS SATISFACTORY FOR MR. MAREK. CONTACT INSPECTION CENTER TO MAKE THEM AWARE OF THE PROBLEM WITH THIS PACKAGE. I SPOKE WITH ACCOUNT EXECUTIVE JIM PASE FROM CUSTOMER SERVICE IN THE RONKONKOMA CENTER (1773) HE ASSURED ME THAT HE WOULD SPEAK TO THE PEOPLE INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT AND FOLLOW-UP WITH ME BY 7-8-94. SEND A COPY OF THE INCIDENT REPORT AND MY WRITE UP TO LONG ISLAND DISTRICT SAFETY MANAGER. FOLLOW-UP WITH MR. MATEK AND LET HIM KNOW HOW WE CORRECTED THE PROBLEMS.

ON 7/25/94, ON A ROUTINE DISPOSAL DELIVERY TO THE LAIDLAW (CROWLEY) FACILITY IN LA, A SPILL OCCURRED ON I-10.  THE SPILL OCCURRED N THE MORING WHILE ENROUTE TO THAT FACILITY.  THE DRIVER, CHESTER RIOS, WAS RADIOED BY ANOTHER TRUCK THAT A SOLVENT SMELL WAS PRESENT AROUND HIS VEHICLE. CHESTER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND INVESTIGATED THE INTERIOR OF THE VAN.  AT THIS POINT, CHESTER USED THE CB TO ALERT OTHER TRUCK TO CALL TO THE HIGHWAY PATROL AND BACK TO OUR FACILITY.  WORD GOT TO US AND A TRUCK WAS DISPATCHED AT 7:30 AM TO ASSIST N THE SPILL CLEANUP.  THEIR APPROXIMATED TIME OF ARRIVAL WAS 10:30 AM.  UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE RESPONSE CREW THEY REMOVED THE BOOMS FROM AROUND THE LEAKING DRUM AND THREW DOWN SOME OIL DRI TO SOAK UP ANY RESIDUAL SOLVENT. IT WAS  FOUND THAT A LOOSE RING ON ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD POPPED OFF AND THE SOLVENT WAS SLOSHING OUT OF DRUM.  THIS DRUM WAS ISOLATED AND A NEW RING AND LID WERE PLACED ON IT.  ANY OUTSIDE WASTE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SURROUNDING DRUMS AND A LAYER OF OIL DRI WAS APLIED TO THE GROUND.  A TOTAL OF ONE PINT WAS RELEASED TO THE SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY.  ALL PERTINENT PAPERWORK FROM THE STATE POLICE AND THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WAS COMPLETED AND THE REPRESENTATIVES FROM BOTH AGENECIES RELEASED THE TRUCK TO CONTINUE ITS ROUTE TO CORWLEY, LA.
SHIPMENT ARRIVED CHR CC WITH HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP OF PAIL CAUSING LEAKAGE. RECOOPED AND RETURN TO SHIPPER PER EDWIN GUITIERREZ WITH SHPR.

ON 7/22/94 AT APPROXIMTELY 0123 HOURS, I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZMAT COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC, I45 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON ON 45177, INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN OUR SORT CENTER OF THE SAME ADDRESS. THE PACKAGE WAS A FIBREBOARD BOX WITH NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS.  THERE WAS NO SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO ORIENTATION MARKINGS OR LABELS AFFIXED TO THE PACKAGE.  INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  I FOUND 1 X 1 QT GLASS BOTTLE WITH A FRICTIOIN TYPE CLOSURE.  THE CLOSURE WAS SECURED TO THE BOTTLE WITH PACKING TAPE.  ON THE SIDE OF THE BOTTLE WAS "FLAMMABLE".  THE WAS BUBBLE WRAP AROUND THE BOTTLE, AND PEANUTS IN THE FIBREBOARD BOX.  THE CONTENTS OF THE BOTTLE WAS KAMILLLOSAN EXTRACT (MEDICINE NA1993) PER THE MATERIAL SAFETEY DATA SHEET PROVIDED LATER BY THE SHIPPER.  SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING PLEASE BY THE FAA.

CHEVRON ORDERED 7001 GALLONS FOR THIS LOCATION.  OUR DISPATCHER SCOTT WADSTORM WROTE THE TRIP TICKET UP FOR 7500 GALLONS.  THE DRIVER DON BAILEY WAS GIVEN A COPY OF THE CHEVRON DISPATCH SLIP BUT DID NOT NOTICE IT WAS FOR 7001 GALLONS.  DON LOADED AND DELIVERED 7500 GALLONS.   UPON ARRIVING DON WENT INSIDE TO HAVE FRED SIGN HIS TRIP TICKET THAT HE COULD HOLD THE PRODUCT.  FRED SIGNED THE TRIP TICKET BUT WROTE BY HIS NAME THAT HE COULD ONLY HOLD 7000 GALLONS.  FRED STATES THAT HE EVEN TOLD DON THAT THAT'S ALL HE COULD HOLD.  DON STATES THAT FRED DID NOT TELL HIM THAT DON DID NOT NOTICE WHAT FRED WROTE,  WHEN DON WAS ALMOST DONE PUMPING OFF, THE PRODUCT BLEW OUT THE TOP OF THE TANK.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE SPILL RETENTION AREA.  CHEVRON WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY CALLED OUT A SPILL CLEAN-UP COMPANY TO CLEAN THE SPILL UP.

A.D. MATY MADE INSPECTION WHICH REVEALED VAPOR LEAKING FROM BENEATH THE MANWAY COVER PLATE; TOP INSPECTION REVEALED LIQUID RUNNING DOWN THE LET SIDE FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  FOUND ONE OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER SWING BOLTS MERELY HAND TIGHT AND ONE WAS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  REMOVED INTACT SEAL "IRECO 10019" FROM MANWAY SWING BOLT AND OPENED THE MANWAY.  IT WAS NOTED THE COVER PLATE HAD A FITTED GASKET WHICH FITS IN A GROOVE WHICH APPEARED THAT APPROXIMMATELY 6 INCHES OF THE GASKET WAS MISSING.  REMOVED THE OLD GASKET AND APPLIED "GORTEX" GASKET MATERIAL TO THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  HAD SWITCH ENGINE HANDLE CAR AND NOTED NO EVIDENCE ON ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND WASHED OFF.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  NOTIFIED CHEMTREC JOE BARBER THEIR REPORT #30038.  THESE EXCEPTIONS WERE DISCUSSED WITH MR. MIKE KELLY CORPORATE OFFICES OF DYNO IN SLC (901-566-1714).  ALSO PLANT MANAGER AT CARTHAGE MISSOURI MR. STEVE TALLEY (417-358-4061) MR TALLEY REQUESTED THAT THE OLD GASKET WHICH WAS REMOVED BE SENT TO HIM, WHICH WAS DONE.

column168: A TELEPHONE CALL FROM JERRY PEERY, CLAIMS, PALESTINE TEXAS, REQUESTING INFORMATION IN REGARD TO CONTAINER EKLU 290656 PLACARDED FLAMMABLE 3, THAT HAD BEEN NOTED TO BE LEAKING FRIDAY 071594.  THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION HAD BEEN ISOLATED.  FURTHER INVESTIGHATION DEVELOPED THAT CONTAINER HAD BEEN LEAKING FROM THE FRONT 1/3RD PORTION.  THE PRODUCT THAT LEAKED APPEARED TO HAVE COAGULATED AND WAS HANGING IN GOSSAMER STRANDS.  INTERIOR INSPECTION NOTED CONTAINER TO BE LOADED WITH 5 GALLON METAL PAILS OF SUPER DIAMOND CLEAR ON PALLETS WRAPPED WITH SHRINK WRAP, WITH OTHER FREIGHT STACKED ON TOP.  HOWEVER, THE FLOOR WAS NOTED WET.  DAVID HUDAK, OPERATION MANAGER, EUCLID CHEMICAL CO., CLEVELAND, OHIO WAS CONTACTED AND HE CONTRACTED DIRECTLY WITH ARTIC OVERSEAS PACKAGING, SEATTLE TO RECOOP AND CLEAN CONTAINER EKLU290656.  RICHARD LEE, GENERAL MANAGER, ARTIC OVERSEAS PACKAGING, SEATTLE WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED SIX OF THE 324 FIVE GALLON METAL PAILS OF SUPER DIAMOND CLEAR, FLAMMABLE N.O.S. 3, WERE NOTED TO BE LEAKING. column168: AT 1530 HOURS ON THURSDAY THE 21ST OF JULY MGR H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY M.T.O. JOHN LYON AT OGDEN, REGARDING TANKCAR GATX 73788.  IT WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AND WAS SENT OUT IN THE UPFE TRACK FOR REPAIR.  INSPECTION UPON ARRIVAL REVEALED THE RUPTURE DISC TO BE BROKEN.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO HAVE THE PROPER DISC SHIPPED BY OVER NITE CARRIER.  ON SATURDAY, JULY 23RD REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED, WITH APPILCATION OF BS & B 4 INCH STAINLESS STEEL, 6O PSIG DISC. BOTH SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT, CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  AT 1830 HRS ON WEDNESDAY THE 26TH OF JULY MGR H.W. RODABOUGH WAS ONCE AGAIN CALLED TO OGDEN , BY M.T.O. CHERYL MOORE, SHE REPORTS TANKCAR GATX3788 IS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  INSPECTION UPON ARRIVAL REVEALED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS BROKEN.  THIS BEING THE SECOND TIME IN LESS THAN A WEEK ON THE SAME CAR, MR. RODABOUGH OPENED THE CAR AND CHECKED FOR OVERLOAD, FINDING THE CAR TO BE PROPERLY LOADED.  HE OBSERVED THAT THERE WERE NO BAFFLES IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY.  CHECK WITH FMC DETERMINED THAT THE CAR HAD NOT BEEN RETROFITED WITH BAFFELS AND THERE WAS NO OBVIOUS REASON FOR THE REOCURRUBG PROBLEM,  A SECOND DISC WAS APPLIED TO THE CAR AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CAR INTERCHANGED TO SOUTHERN PACIFIC AT OGDEN AND DELIVERED TO DESTINATION.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT ZERWECK WAS CALLED TO CENTENNIAL YARD TO CHECK CAR NDTX 34478 AFTER CARMEN REPORTED SMELLING AMMONIA WHEN THEY PASSED IT. ZERWECK REMOVED SEAL 040709 FROM THE MANWAY COVER.  THE NEEDLE VALVE ON THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE WAS NOT TIGHT AND AFTER TIGHTENING THE VAPOR LEAK STOPPED.  IN ADDITION, THE PLUGS ON THE LIQUID LINES WERE NOT WRENCH TIGHT, HOWEVER THEY WERE NOT LEAKING.  SEAL UPRO43743 WAS APPLIED AFTER CLOSING THE COVER.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 2126 HOURS.  VANCE BERRY, C R FIND INDUSTRIES DONALDSONVILLE (504-473-8291) WAS NOTIFIED ON 072094 AT 1300.

PACKAGE DISCOVERED BY RESPONDER C. NELSON AND REMOVED FROM BELT. PACKAGE CHECKED BY RESPONDER, NO 5 PART OR DIAMOND LABEL ON PACKAGE. PACKAGE CONTAINED FIBERGLASS RESIN UN1866. column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Weld or Seam
column168: SHAWN LYNCH WAS UNLOADING TRAILER #34109 WHEN HE CAME ACROSS A LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE. HE IMMEDIATELY BROUGH IT TO THE ATTENTION OF RICK PARSION SUPERVISOR RICK MOVED SHAWN TO OTHER LOAD AND THEN WENT TO DMP AREA TO THE SPILL CART. RICK USED THE DECISION TREE ON DETERMINING WHICH PPE ROUSE AND HOW TO HANDLE LEAKING PACKAGE. WHEN BROUGHT TO DMP AREA RICK PROCESSED IMMEDIATELY. THIS OCCURED AT 5:35 AM.

AT 18:20, MIKE PATTERSON (SUPERVISOR) FOUND THE LEAKING PACKAGE INSIDE A TRAILER. HE THEN BROUGHT IT TO THE DMP AREA AND IDENTIFIED IT AS DICHLOROMETHANE. AT 20:45 ED DAVIS (FIRST RESPONDER) TOOK THE LEAKING CONTAINER TO A TABLE IN THE DMP AREA, WHERE HE THEN REFERRED TO THE DECISION TREE AND CONTINUED TO PROCESS THE PACKAGE USING THE NEEDED PPE EQUIPMENT AND ABSORBENT. HE TIGHTENED A LOOSE CAP ON THE LEAKING CONTAINER AND SENT TO THE SHIPPER AND DISPOSED OF CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM.

ESTES ENROUTE TO CONSIGNEE WHEN HE STOPPED AND ASKED DIRECTIONS, UPON RETURNING TO UNIT DISCOVERED LEAK, AT THAT TIME HE CALLED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. HE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR TO DISCOVER THE DRUM HAD BROKEN LOOSE FROM THE SKID. IT HAD BEEN STRAPPED TO THE SKID. LOCAL FIRE DEPT AND US NAVY HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED TO ASSIST AND CONTAIN SPILL. ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND PLACED IN OVERPACK AND RETURNED TO WINCHESTER, VA. CURRENTLY AWAITING FOR LAB RESULTS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. WAS ADVISED BY LOCAL FIRE CHIEF THAT "SEVERAL" EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE OVERCOME BY HEAT AS THEY WERE SUITED UP IN LEVEL A RESPONSE GEAR AND TEMPERTURE WAS IN HIGH 90'S AND HUMIDITY WAS HIGH AS WELL. RECEIVED UNCONFIRMED REPORTS RESPONDERS MAY HAVE RECEIVED ACID BURNS WHILE TRYING TO RESCUE RESPONDERS IN TRAILER. REPORTED TO NRC ON DATE OF INCIDENT #249883 TO PETTY OFFICER GARNEAU. ADVISED THREE BUSINESSES WERE CLOSED AS RESULT OF INCIDENT UNABLE TO DETERMINE NUMBER OF PEOPLE EVACUATED. THE INTERSECTION WAS CLOSED FROM APPROXIMATELY 1200 TO 1900 HRS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 A.M. TUESDAY JULY 12TH I RECEIVED A CALL FROM TOM WINTERS INFORMING ME THAT ED WINTERS HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A ONE VEHICLE IN THE COMPANY TRUCK UNIT #35 AND THE ACCIDENT WAS ON THE EAST SIDE OF BERTHOUD PASS. TOM INFORMED ME THAT ED WAS NOT INJURED HOWEVER THE TRUCK WAS ON ITS SIDE AND FUEL WAS LEAKING FROM THE FRONT COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER. I IMMEDIATELY CALLED ALEC BROWN AND SENT HIM TO THE CRASH SITE TO AID PUMPING OFF THE DAMAGED TRAILER. I WAS CONTACTED BY MARY THE DISPATCHER FOR THE COLORADO STATE PATROL, SHE NEEDED INFORMATION ON WHO HAD BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE WRECK/SPILL. AND HOW SOON THEY WOULD BE THERE TO START CLEANUP AND PUMPING FUEL FROM TRAILER SO THEY COULD REMOVE THE TRUCK AND TRAILER FROM THE AREA. MARY INFORMED ME THAT HIGHWAY 40 WAS CLOSED IN BOTH DIRECTIONS BECAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT AND HAZARDOUS CLEANUP AND PUMP OFF THE DAMAGED TRAILER NEEDED TO BE IMMEDIATE. I WENT TO THE FLEISCHLI OFFICE AND CALLED THE MAIN OFFICE IN CHEYENNE, AND RECEIVED JEFF LOGRY'S PHONE NUMBER FROM THE RECORDING. I THEN CALLED JEFF AND TOLD HIM OF THE EMERGENCY AND RECEIVED JERRY JOHN'S PHONE NUMBER. JERRY JOHN HELPED ME WITH REPORTING INFORMATION AND WHAT NEEDED DONE FIRST AND WHERE TO GET THE INFORMATION I NEEDED. I CALLED ALL THE AGENCY'S LISTED FOR HAZARDOUS CLEANUP AND COULD NOT CONTACT ANYONE. I THEN  CALLED MARY THE DISPATCHER FROM THE STATE PATROL. MARY ASKED COLORADO STATE PATROL (HAZMAT OFFICER) DAN ALLISON AND REFERRED TO ME A LIST OF AGENCY'S TO TRY. I CONTACTED WEST HAZMAT FROM THE LIST. DAVE WITH WEST HAZMAT CONTACTED ME AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00 A.M. GATHERED AS MANY DETAILS AS HE COULD AND SAID HE WOULD HAVE A CREW ON SITE WITHIN THE NEXT TWO HOURS. I THEN CALLED MARY TO INFORM HER THAT WEST HAZMAT WOULD BE ARRIVING AND APPROXIMATELY WHAT TIME. SHORTLY AFTER THAT TIME JIM RYAN WITH WEST HAZMAT CONTACTED ME TO CONFIRM DETAILS. JIM SAID HE WOULD BE THE CREW FOREMAN AND THAT HIS CREW WAS ON THEIR WAY. AT THIS TIME IT WAS APPROXIMATELY 4:15 A.M. I CALLED THE NATIONAL REPSONSE CENTER, DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL. I REPORTED THE SPILL AND ACCIDENT TO PETTY OFFICER WILKINSON AND RECEIVED A CASE REFERENCE NUMBER #248940 FROM HIM. I THEN CONTACTED THE COLORADO DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AT 4:30 A.M. AND REPORTED TO THE ANSWERING SERVICE, THEY INFORMED ME THEY WOULD CALL BACK. STEVE GUNDERSON WITH THE COLORADO DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH CALLED AT ABOUT 4:45 AND I REPORTED THE SPILL AND CONTAMINATION WITH ALL THE DETAILS THAT  I HAD AT THAT TIME. THAT POSSIBLY 2500 GALLONS OF DIESEL HAD BEEN RELEASED AND SOME WAS IN A NEARBY STREAM. I RECEIVED THE PHONE NUMBER FOR THE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH ENVIRONMENTAL SPILL EMERGENCY HOTLINE NUMBER 765-4455. I CALLED AND RECEIVED ANOTHER NUMBET FROM THE RECORDING 890-1669. I THEN RECEIVED A CALL FROM STEVE GUNDERSON, TELLING ME THAT BY CALLING HIM, AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE THAT E.P.A. HAD BEEN NOTIFIED. AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 I CALLED THE COLORADO STATE PATROL OFFICE AND MARY GAVE ME A UPDATE ON THE

HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR FRANCES K. VANCE AND P/T HAZ MAT SOIL TECHNICIAN RANDY WILLIAMS RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL WERE FOUND A FIBREBOARD BOX LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID. column168: WHILE THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING, THE TANK OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICE CLOSED.  PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE VAPOR FITTING AROUND THE CONNECTION TO THE UNDERGROUND TANK.  THIS CAUSED THE CONTAINMENT BOX TO OVERFILL AND PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE ASPHALT DRIVEWAY.  PRODUCT FLOW WAS STOPPED AND THE AREA WAS COVERED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL.  SPILL WAS CAUSED BY A MALFUNCTION IN THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM.  NECESSARY REPAIRS HAVE BEEN MADE TO CORRECT THIS MALFUNCTION.

column168: 0815 HOURS, FRIDAY, JULY 29TH, 1994 MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY STU WHITED WAS NOTIFIED THAT CAR GATX 12283, BUTYLACRYLATE HAD BEEN DELIVERED TO THE EJ & E RAILROAD AT CHICAGO HEIGHTS LATE ON JULY 28TH, AND THE EJ & E RAILROAD HAD REPORTED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING.  PRODUCT WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT THE RATE OF ONE DROP EVERY FIFTY SECONDS.  THE PRODUCT WAS BEING COLLECTED IN A FIVE GALLON BUCKET LINED WITH DIRT TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL.  WHITED IMMEDIATELY DEPARTED ST LOUIS ARRIVING EJ & E YARD CHICAGO HEIGHTS, IL., 1255 HOURS, SAME DATE.  ON ARRIVAL, HE FOUND THAT THE CAR WAS NOT LEAKING AND THE FIVE GALLON BUCKET WAS MISSING.  HE INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND ALL MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE TIGHT.  TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE COVER CABLE WAS SEALED.  BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS TIGHT.  WHITED CONTACTED EJ & E DISPATCHER AND ADVISED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN CHECKED AND WAS OK FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.  WHITED CONTACTED MR. BOB KOCH AT BASF, FREEPORT, TEXAS.  HE WAS UNAWARE THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN REPORTED TO HIS OFFICE BY MIKE STEFFINS, EJ & E YARDMASTER.  HIS OFFICE CONTACTED HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL WHO SECURED THE LEAK.  THEY DISPOSED OF RELEASED MATERIAL AND FIVE GALLON BUCKET.

I, FRANCIS VANCE, RESPONDED TO A SPILL AT OUR SORT FACILITY AT 145 HUNTER DR., WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. SPILL, WAS LOCATED IN BUILDING B AT DOOR B-25. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED AS A CLEAR LIQUID, WITH AN ODOR OF ALCOHOL WITH ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT. I FRANCIS VANCE, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR AND JON MOOTS, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TECH., ARRIVED ON SCENE TO FIND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX, WHICH HAD EVIDENCE OF SHIPMENT LEAKING. BOX HAD NO MARKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS HAZARDOUS. UPON OPENING THE BOX, SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO CONTAIN FIVE SMALL GLASS CONTAINERS APX. 4OZ. CAPACITY IN SIZE. ONE OF THE CONTAINERS WAS CRUSHED AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS HAD LEAKED (CYCLOHEXANUNE). ONE CONTAINER OF METHYL ETHYL KETONE WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WAS FOUND TO BE IMPROPERLY PLACED IN PACKAGE. NO OTHER CONTAINERS SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL INVESTIGATED AND RELEASED BY THE FAA.
NO REMARKS

column168: DRIVER KEN BOUFFORD CALLED IN AT 15:30 AND REPORTED LEAKING WET HAZARDOUS PACKAGE ON FLOOR OF HIS VEHICLE.  BEING ONLY A BLOCK AWAY HE BROUGHT HIS CAR BACK TO THE BUILDING WHERE FIRST RESPONDER PAUL TANGUAY AND WILLIAM PAIGE REMOVED PACKAGE TO SPILL BUCKET WITH SOLUSORB ABSORBENT WHICH WAS DETERMINED AFTER USING THE DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  WEARING APPROPRIATE PE FROM RESPONSE SHEET PACKAGE WAS TRANSFERRED TO DMP AREA WHERE IT WAS PROCESSED AND DECONTAMINATION WAS COMPLETED BY 17:15.

LEO BOISVERT CAME IN PSC AND TOLD MARY COLIN THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING CORROSIVE AT WILMINGTON SLIDE.  HE BROUGHT ONE OF THE FIVE PART LABEL WITH HIM.  USING THAT AND THE DECISION TREE, WITH PROPER PPE I WENT TO GET IT. THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED TO BOX WITH ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT ON SLIDE.  I CLEANED IT UP WITH A PAPER TOWEL.  BROUGHT BACK TO DMP, PUT ALL WET CARDBOARD, PAPER TOWEL AND GLOVE IN DMP BAG.  ADD SODIUM BICARBONATE TO BAG AND PUT THROUGH DMP PROCEDURE.  FINISHED AT 17:50.

WHEN OUR ASSOCIATE WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER, THESE BOXES APPEARED TO BE SOILED. THEY WERE IMMEDIATELY PUT ASIDE ON A PALLET AWAY FROM OTHER PRODUCT THAT WAS NOT LEAKING. ALL OF THE BOXES HAD SPILLED MATERIAL ON THEM. THE CARDBOARD WAS ALLOWED TO DRY AND THEN DISPOSED OF PER THE SHIPPER(ATCO MANUFACTURING CO., MARIETTA, GA). FIVE OF THE 40 PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE EMPTY AND THE LIQUID HAD EVAPORATED. BECAUSE THE CARDBOARD WAS UNUSABLE, THE PLASTIC BOTTLES (INCLUDING 4 OF THE EMPTY ONES) WERE SHRINKWRAPPED TO A PALLET AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE (COASTAL CONTRACTORS, BEARFORT, S.C.) PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS. THE FIFTH BOTTLE WAS FORWARDED TO OUR MARIETTA FACILITY TO DAVID HUMPHREY FOR DISCUSSION WITH THE SHIPPER CONCERNING CONTAINER SUITABLILITY FOR THIS PRODUCT.

column168: AT 7:30 AM I RECEIVED A CALL FROM DRIVER EXPLAINING HE WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT WHICH IN TURN CREATED A SPILL. DRIVER ALLEGES HE WAS TRAVELLING NORTH ON 195 WHEN A CAR IN FRONT OF HIM WAS SLOWING DOWN/STOOPING. TO AVOID HITTING CAR, DRIVER APPLIED BRAKES, SWERVED RIGHT, THEN LEFT ON WET PAVEMENT. TRACTOR AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER ON ITS LEFT SIDE NO LEFT SHOULDER OF HIGHWAY. APPROXIMATELY 40 LB. OF PRODUCT SPILLED WHEN LID DETACHED FROM ONE TOTE BIN. VIRGINIA STATE POLICE, HENRICO COUNTY HAZ. MAT. UNIT AND EMERGENCY MEDICAL UNIT RESPONDED. DRIVERS WERE OBSERVED AND RELEASED. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED WHO IN TURN CALLED SHIPPER CLEAN HARBORS WAS CONTRACTED TO CLEAN UP INCIDENT AND REMOVED BINS TO THEIR FACILITY. TRACTOR AND TRAILER  MOVED TO BROYLES GARAGE. THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED BY CARRIER VIA TELEPHONE WITH APPROX. TIME: 11:20 AM - NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (202-267-2675), REPORT #252243; 11:30 AM - STATE OF VIRGINIA HAZ. MAT. RESPONSE (804-527-5200); AND 11:40 AM - HENRICO COUNTY, VA HAZ. MAT. RESPONSE (804-672-4914). NORTHBOUND 195 CLOSED IN EXCESS OF 8 HOURS.
